target: economy
validations:
  - name: money_changes_over_time
    type: agent_validation
    severity: error
    args:
      rubric: >
        Verify that the zoo's balance changes over time as the simulation runs.
        Start a game, build at least one enclosure, and purchase at least one
        animal. Let the simulation run for several ticks. The balance should
        decrease due to food and maintenance costs. Once visitors begin arriving,
        the balance should also receive income from admissions. The net change
        should be visible in the financial HUD.

  - name: admission_price_affects_visitors
    type: agent_validation
    severity: error
    args:
      rubric: >
        Verify that changing the admission price affects visitor behavior. Set
        up a zoo with animals and enclosures so that visitors are arriving. Note
        the visitor arrival rate at the default price. Raise the admission price
        significantly and observe that fewer visitors arrive per tick. Lower the
        price well below the original and observe that more visitors arrive.
        The relationship between price and visitor count should follow a demand
        curve where higher prices reduce volume.

  - name: game_over_on_bankruptcy
    type: agent_validation
    severity: error
    args:
      rubric: >
        Verify that the game ends when the zoo goes bankrupt. Create a scenario
        where expenses exceed revenue — for example, buy many expensive animals
        but set the admission price extremely high so almost no visitors come.
        Let the simulation run until the balance reaches zero. The game should
        detect the bankruptcy condition and display a game-over screen showing
        the final animal count and other summary statistics.
